  "text": "35 S]methionine in vivo revealed that both wild-type and mrpl36⌬C cells synthesize all eight mitochondrially encoded proteins ( Figure 2A ). However, the amount of radiolabeled proteins in mrpl36⌬C was lower than in wild-type cells, in particular for COX subunits. The most severe reduction was found for Cox1, which has been reported not to be efficiently synthesized in mutants defective in COX assembly [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . However, overexpression of the translational activator of Cox1, Mss51, did not mitigate the growth defect (data not shown). Cox2, which is synthesized as a precursor protein with an N-terminal leader peptide, was processed to its mature form, indicating proper topogenesis in the mutant. Insertion of mitochondrial translation products into the inner membrane and binding of Oxa1 and Mba1 to the ribosome were not changed in mrpl36⌬C mitochondria (Supplemental Figure 1) . Apparently, mitochondrial translation of the mrpl36⌬C cells can produce all the mitochondrially encoded polypeptides. Similarly, all the membrane proteins are inserted efficiently into the inner membrane.",
